AB  - Knowledge management in resource-intensive and big data applications involving multiple parties where collaboration is a pre-requisite to the successful operation of the system remains a topic of much-needed innovation, especially in the wake of growing resource-intensive applications such as disaster management and smart environments. Analysis of existing literature reveals the growing need to tackle the issue of unified data dissemination. Where this issue has been given some focus, the outreach has been more or less limited to similar systems (i.e. cross-instance collaboration) and no particular focus has been applied on the problem of exposing this data or knowledge to third parties (i.e. crossvendor collaboration), which necessitates integration of semantic technologies. This paper proposes an integration of semantic technologies within the Web of Things based on the concept and principles of the Service-Oriented Architecture to realize a semi-autonomous multi-party collaboration framework that is capable of offering cross-vendor information exchange and collaboration facilities. Powered by the JENA semantic engine and exposed as a web application with a RESTful API, the generic framework offers an extensible knowledge management system for dynamic Web of Things applications. Disaster management is taken as a potential application scenario to critically analyse and evaluate the system prototype and show that the proposed framework is capable of meeting the ever-increasing needs of cross-vendor information sharing and exchange needs in today's applications. The paper presents an analysis of tag-based semantic profiling and annotation of devices in a distributed sensor network and discusses the correlation of increased profiling accuracy and reduced mapping ambiguity with an increase in the number and quality of tags provided during the profiling phase. The paper concludes by asserting that tag-based semantic profiling of network assets is an effective and maintainable mechanism for the semantic annotation of devices and for meeting the knowledge management needs of the Web of Things.
