AB  - Natural hazards become natural disasters as volcanic eruption, earthquake, landslide, tsunami and so on when they affect people and the structures that they live in, and/or disrupt delicate ecosystems. Natural disasters weaken the societal infrastructure and cost billions of Euros each year in economic losses. Proper evaluation of the natural hazards and their possible effects on the population and the environment is critical for minimizing the number of casualties, reduce economical and other losses and activate recovery processes. Nowadays modern technologies and surveying techniques could provide a valuable and efficient tool, useful to prevent and mitigate calamitous events, natural disasters and dangerous situations. The architecture and the logical scheme for such kind of applicative solutions, outlines that the main goal to pursue is represented by the integration of different technologies supported by a rational use of the communication infrastructures by robust software management and processing tools. In this context space technology is demonstrating to be one of the key element for the emergency management in relation to the fact that the disasters have often a large-scale and those most affected by disasters are often the poor and socially disadvantaged in developing country where the lack of infrastructure (e.g. communication) causes an increasing loss of lives. This abstract aims at emphasizing how space-based technology systems can support several aspects of the emergency management in crisis scenarios underlining that the primary need is a synergic approach involving satellite communication, satellite navigation (GPS/EGNOS/Galileo), earth observation systems (e.g. GMES), meteorological satellites, national space based systems, etc. with the need of extending this synergy to other technological areas such as the information technology to constitute a world wide monitoring and alerting system. The development of the new European Global Navigation Satellite System Galileo, its interoperability with the Global Positioning System, and the use of the European Geostationary Navigation Overlay System (EGNOS), will contribute substantially to the quantity and quality of the satellite measurements thereby improving for example the quality of the deformation monitoring process. Moreover the possibility to broadcast messages by means of SBAS systems (EGNOS for Europe) is of considerable interest for the organization of a global alerting system promoting Galileo and the SBAS as candidate for a rapid implementation of a zone-related early-warning system. The main research lines to be explored are represented by data fusion from the earth observation systems and the global navigation satellite systems data, due to their complementary nature and in relation to their rapid evolution (GMES, Galileo and EGNOS development). In particular GNSS techniques and DIFferential Synthetic Aperture Radar Interferometry (DIFSAR) shows to be complementary both in space and in time domains. For example integrating GNSS sensor networks with DIFSAR images represents a viable approach for filtering out atmospheric and/or orbital artifacts. Not only, using a surface short-term deformation model, monitored by DIFSAR at repeat times, it is possible to generate innovative algorithms for global spatial interpolation of GNSS discrete data at continuous times. Another important aspect is represented by the communications that can be for such kind of application the bottleneck for different factors: unavailability of terrestrial signal, temporary unavailability of terrestrial infrastructure and so on. For this reason a redundant satellite channel is essential to assure a reliable communication system all over the world by means of different satellite communication system as IRIDIUM; GLOBALSTAR, etc.. Therefore it is clear how the satellite-based technology can influence and enhance the effectiveness and efficiency in each of the emergency lifecycle phases: prevention, preparation, response and recovery. Thales Alenia Space Italia, with the Applications Development Unit and other related department (Earth Observation, Telecommunication, etc.) is directly involved in the study of end-to-end solutions aimed to fulfill the needs of problems related to the Emergency Management focusing the interest and objectives of ongoing projects and research and development activities in a wider and international context.
